1 Introduction

This project examines the condition of various bridges in the US. The dataset has information about the bridge condition and some covariates that can help in explaining that condition. This report summarizes the process of exploratory data analysis (EDA), proposing a linear regression model with its interpretation and diagnostics, and finally make some prediction for new data. The variables in the dataset are as follows:

Variable Description
Structure_id Identification key
Urban Whether the bridge is in an urban or rural area
Year The year the bridge was built
Lanes_on Number of traffic lanes on the bridge
AverageDaily The average daily traffic (number of vehicles)
Historic Whether the bridge is historic
Material The dominant material the bridge is made from
Spans Number of spans of the bridge
Length The length of the bridge (m)
Width The width of the bridge (m)
Trucks_percent The percentage of traffic made up of trucks

2 Data Preparation

We now load the data, assuming that the two .csv files are in data folder. Based on the dataset description, we know that Urban, Historic, and Material are categorical covariates, which corresponds to factor in R.

data <- read_csv("data/group_04.csv", col_types = cols(
  Urban = col_factor(),
  Historic = col_factor(),
  Material = col_factor(),
))

We now take a quick look at summary of the data. As we can see, there are 10 covariates, 3 of which are categorical. The minimum and maximum values of all variables but Spans are reasonable. Since bridges with 0 spans do not exist, we decide to remove these cases in the data. In addition, the striking low number of bridges built with Masonry compared to other materials could lead to low precision (high standard error) when estimating model coefficients. With that low number, we also cannot make any conclusion about bridges built with masonry. Therefore, we decide to join Masonry and Other into one level.

3 Exploratory Data Analysis

3.1 Numerical covariates

We first take a look at the numeric covariates and their distribution. To achieve this, we plot their histograms, shown in FigureÂ 1.

data |> 
  select(where(is.numeric), -c(Condition)) |> 
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "covariate") |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=value)) +
  facet_wrap(~covariate, scales = "free", nrow=3)

From the plots, we can see that the distributions of the covariates are fairly skewed, especially AverageDaily, Length, Width and Spans, where the range of the values is very wide but most of them fall into a very small area, specifically near zero. This may require a log transformation to make the data more symmetrical.

We now focus our attention on the response variable, Condition, whose histogram is shown in FigureÂ 2.

data |> 
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Condition), binwidth = 1)

We can see that the distribution is symmetrical around 21. Next, we examine the relation between numerical covariates and the response variable. First, based on the scatterplot (FigureÂ 3, the x-axis is in log-scale for clear display of skewed distribution), we can see that there is no specific pattern between all covariates and Condition. Most of them also seem to exhibit little correlation with the response variable, indicated by the fairly flat fitted line. Year seems to have the largest positive correlation with Condition, which is further confirmed in FigureÂ 4. We expect that older bridges have worse condition than new ones.

data |> 
  select(where(is.numeric)) |> 
  pivot_longer(-Condition, names_to = "covariate", values_to = "Values") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Values, y = Condition)) +

GGally::ggcorr(data)

As for the correlation between covariates, we notice that Lanes_on and Width has remarkably high positive correlation, while other pairs such as Lanes_on and AverageDaily, Length and Spans and Width and AverageDaily shows moderately positive correlation. On the other hand, Year and Trucks_percent has moderately negative correlation, indicating that more trucks cross older bridges.

There are three categorical covariates in the dataset, namely Historic, Urban and Material. First, we plot the heat map of counts for Historic and Material corresponding to the levels of Urban (FigureÂ 5). It is clearly seen that most bridges are either not historic or possibly historic. In terms of the Material, Steel and Concrete are the most common ones.

4 Methods

4.1 Model proposal

We propose three models to analyze how the covariates may explain the condition of bridges.

  1. A multiple linear regression model with no interaction.
  2. A multiple linear regression model with transformation for some covariates and no interaction.
  3. A multiple linear regression model with interactions.

For model 2, we decide to log-transform Width, Length, AverageDaily, Trucks_percent and Spans due to the skewness and large range of the values. Also, it might be easier to interpret the coefficients after log-transformation as different in Condition mean when increasing covariates in proportions.

For model 3, when adding interactions, we consider the following points:

  • log(Length) * log(Spans): Long bridges with more spans are more strong, which means their condition might be better.
  • log(AverageDaily + 1) * Material and log(Trucks_percent + 1) * Material: The amount of daily trafficâs impact on bridge condition might depend on the material used to build the bridge, as different materials have different capacity tolerate pressure. This is similar for the percentage of trucks.
  • Year:Material: Similarly, bridges built with different material might have different wear-out rate over time.
model <- lm(Condition ~ ., data = select(data, -Structure_id))
model2 <- lm(Condition ~ 
               Urban + Historic + Material + Year + 
               log(AverageDaily + 1) +
               log(Width) + log(Spans) + log(Length) +
               log(Trucks_percent + 1) + Lanes_on, data = dplyr::select(data, -Structure_id))
model3 <- lm(Condition ~ Urban + Historic +
               Year * Material +log(AverageDaily + 1) * Material +
               log(Trucks_percent + 1) * Material +
               log(Spans) * log(Length) + 
               log(Width) + Lanes_on, data = dplyr::select(data, -Structure_id))

An \(R^2\) value of 0.4652 means that the model is only able to explain 46.52% of the variance in the response.

We first call our attention to the high p-values of coefficients corresponding to Urban level of Urban covariate and Other level of Material covariate. In this dummy variable coding, Rural and Concrete are used as the reference level, respectively.

  • For Urban, this means that there is no significant change in the response (Condition) when comparing two bridges in urban and rural, holding other variables constant. It might be the case that Urban does not help much in explaining the bridge condition. This is also reflected in the small value of the coefficient (-0.0240).
  • However, for Other level of Material, the coefficient is not that small (-0.2911), however, the standard error is high (0.2289), leading to high p-value. This may be explained by the low number of bridges built with Other material (only 52), leading to imprecise estimation of the coefficient.

Despite having very low p-values, which means statistical significance, some covariates, namely AverageDaily, Length, Width, Spans and Trucks_percent have very small coefficients (and also very small standard error, which leads to low p-values). This might be explained by high range of values of these covariates in the dataset, which lead to our choice of log-transformation.

After log-tranforming the data, the coefficients are now larger, accurately reflecting the impact of these covariates on the bridge condition. Specifically:

  • For a 100% increase in AverageDaily, the expected bridge condition decreases by 0.0163 points. This indicates that bridges with more traffic tend to have worse condition.
  • Similarly, for a 100% increase in Width and Length, the expected bridge condition increases by 0.7080 and 0.0249 points, respectively. This indicates that wider and longer bridges tend to have better condition.
  • However, Spans and Lanes_on seem to have a negative effect on bridge condition.
  • It is also confirmed that newer bridges tend to have better condition. When comparing two bridges with 1 year difference in age (everything else similar), the expected difference in Condition is 0.0510 points.

For categorical covariates, the following points can be made:

  • Comparing similar bridges with only different values in Historic, bridges that are Possible or Register have better condition than Not Historic (the reference level). The reason might be that historic bridges receive more maintenance than normal ones.
  • The material used to build bridges also affect their condition. Specifically, all the coeffients of Material dummy variables are negative, except for Masonry, suggesting that bridges built with Concrete have better condition than Timber and Steel, which is reasonable.

To compare the âeffectsâ of different covariates, we standardize the coefficients and plot their values, shown in FigureÂ 7. It can be seen that Year seem to be the most important in explaining bridges condition, as expected from its high correlation with Condition in the Explanatory Data Analysis section. In contrast, Material seems to negatively affect bridge condition the most.

The interaction term Year:MaterialSteel is negative and statistically significant (-0.0093). This adjusts the slope for Steel bridges to roughly 0.044 (\(0.053 - 0.009\)). This lower slope suggests that the condition gap between old and new steel bridges is smaller than that of concrete bridges. This implies that Concrete bridges seem to show a faster rate of deterioration over time than Steel bridges. However, the interaction for Timber was not statistically significant (\(p = 0.269\)), suggesting Timber bridges deteriorate at a similar rate to Concrete in this dataset.

The interaction term log(Spans):log(Length) is positive (+0.060). This confirms our intuition that increasing the number of spans for a given length helps mitigate the drop in condition. Physically, this implies that a long bridge divided into many shorter spans (shorter average span length) is structurally more robust or resilient than a long bridge with fewer, longer spans.

4.3 Model diagnostics

4.3.1 Diagnostic plots

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

FigureÂ 8, FigureÂ 9 and FigureÂ 10 shows the diagnostic plots based on resisuals corresponding to model 1, 2 and 3. Based on these plots, we can assess the assumptions of linear regression model:

  • Linearity: Looking at the residual plots, we can see the mean of the residuals is close to 0 for every value of fitted value. Therefore, there seems not to be a problem with this assumption.
  • Normality: The QQ plots show slightly deviation from the line at its both tail. However, most of the data points fit into the line, indicating that slight deviation is also not a major problem.
  • Homoscedasticity: Looking at the residual plots, the spread of the residuals are mostly even across different fitted values. The scale-location plots also show a relatively flatline measuring the magnitude of the resiuals.
  • Correlated error: The residual plots do not show specific patterns.
  • Outlier: While the residual plots show some outlier, the Residual vs Leverage plots show that no points have large Cook distance (\(>0.5\)), which means there are no leverage points.

4.4 Building Linear Regression model for prediction

4.4.1 More complex models

We propose another model with polynomial terms based on model 3 (the model with highest adjusted \(R^2\)), which may improve the predictive capacity. Based on figure FigureÂ 7, we give high power to Year, AverageDaily, Width and Spans as these seem to be important in predicting the condition.

model3_poly <- lm(Condition ~ Urban*Historic +
               poly(Year, 5) * Material + 
               poly(log(AverageDaily + 1), 5) * poly(log(Width), 4) +
               poly(log(AverageDaily + 1), 5) * poly(log(Length + 1), 2) +
               poly(log(Spans + 1), 4) * poly(log(Length + 1), 2) +
               poly(log(Trucks_percent + 1), 2) * Material +
               poly(log(AverageDaily + 1), 5) * Material + 
               I(Width/Lanes_on), data = dplyr::select(data, -Structure_id))

4.4.2 Model evaluation

We decide to evaluate the models based on the following metrics:

  • Adjusted \(R^2\): Adjusted \(R^2\) penalizes for the number of predictors \(p\), using the formula: \(\text{Adjusted } R^2 = 1 - (1 - R^2) \frac{n-1}{n-p-1}\).
  • Akaike Information Criterion (AIC): \(\text{AIC} = -2 \log(\mathcal{L}) + 2p\), where \(\mathcal{L}\) is the maximized likelihood, and \(p\) is the number of parameters. AIC estimates the relative quality of models for prediction, balancing goodness-of-fit (via log-likelihood) with parsimony. Lower AIC values are preferred.
  • Predicted Residual Error Sum of Squares (PRESS): PRESS is a direct measure of predictive performance, computed via leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV): for each observation \(i\), refit the model excluding it, predict its value, and square the residual, then take the sum: \(\text{PRESS} = \sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y}_{(-i)})^2\)
  • k-fold Cross Validation (k = 8): Splits data into 8 folds; trains on 7 and tests on 1, then computing the root mean square prediction error (RMSPE) across folds. This provides robust estimate of predictive performance.
models <- list(model, model2, model3, model12, model22, model3_poly)
models.names <- c("Simple Model", "Model with Tranformation", 
                      "Model with Interaction", "Simple Model (low VIF)",
                      "Model with Tranformation (low VIF)", "Complex Model")
k <- 8
n <- nrow(data)

set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
folds <- sample(1:k, n, replace = TRUE)

rmspe_results <- matrix(NA, nrow = k, ncol = length(models))
colnames(rmspe_results) <- models.names

# Perform k-fold CV
for (i in 1:k) {
  train_data <- data[folds != i, ]
  test_data  <- data[folds == i, ]
  
  for (j in seq_along(models)) {
    formula <- models[[j]]$call$formula
    fit <- lm(formula, data = select(train_data, -Structure_id))
    pred <- predict(fit, newdata = test_data)
    actual <- test_data$Condition
    rmspe_results[i, j] <- sqrt(mean((actual - pred)^2))
  }
  rm(train_data, test_data, fit, formula, pred)
}
measures <- function(model) {
  summ <- summary(model)
  data.frame(df = summ$df[1],
             adjR2 = summ$adj.r.squared,
             AIC = AIC(model),
             PRESS = sum(rstandard(model, type="pred")^2))
}

results <- do.call(rbind, lapply(models, measures))
results$RMSPE <- colMeans(rmspe_results)
rownames(results) <- models.names
results

As can be seen in TableÂ 1, the metrics are consistent in evaluating the performance of the models. It can clearly be seen that the model with interaction has better scores than those without interaction, even if these metrics adjust for the number of parameters. The best model is our proposed complex model with polynomial transformations, outperforming other models by a large margin on every metric. Therefore, we choose the last model to predict the condition on new data.

5 Conclusion

In this report, we performed an exploratory data analysis of the bridge dataset and proposed some linear regression models to explain how the covariates can affect the bridge condition. We found out that Year, Width and Material seem to be the most important covariates. As for interaction, most of them are statistically significant, namely Year:Material and Spans:Length, which describes how a covariateâs effect may depend on another. We also took measures to handle the slightly high Variance Inflation Factor of the model. For predicting the condition for a new set of bridges, we propose a new, more complex model with polynomials, which has superior predictive power. This is reflected in our model evaluation, in which we computed several metrics such as AIC, PRESS and RMSPE for k-fold cross validation.
